description.narrative:
The project’s activities are described below at three levels. 
At individual level the project entails:
- the organisation of 16 dialogue sessions for 50 women, men, boys and girls on the risks and dangers of FGM/C and the (SRH) rights of girls and young women. FGM/C impacts the complete physical, mental and social well-being of girls and women, including their (future) sex lives, their ability to have children and their own freedom to decide about these issues (FGM/C is strongly linked to gender inequality and therefore to unequal rights within societies); 
- the organisation of children’s rights debates in 40 primary schools to discuss FGM/C, (SRH) rights issues and violence against women and girls;
- five days training for 60 women’s groups to explore how funding and alternative sources of income can be found for the people who practice (FMG/C);
- developing information and educational materials on the eradication of FGM/C (such as T-shirts, posters, banners, brochures and flyers). 
At community level the project entails:
-   a five-day training of 180 paralegals on the prosecution of children’s-rights violations like FGM/C; 
-   two training sessions for 80 local organisations, such as women’s groups, to include the eradication of FGM/C in all aspects of their work; 
-     three-monthly forums with stakeholders, such as local organisations, women’s and youth groups, in which best practices and lessons are shared and new strategies are jointly developed.
At institutional level the project entails:
-  16 sessions targeting political leaders at county and national levels to influence legislation on FGM/C and develop specific laws both in both county and national legislation; 
- five annual sessions on existing legal instruments for tackling FGM/C for national parliamentarians and local chiefs to explain relevant conventions, the constitution, the Children’s Act 2001 and the Sexual Offences Act 2006;
- the training of approximately 1,000 law enforcers, such as provincial administrators and the police, on relevant legislation that outlaws FGM/C;
- arranging exchange visits to surrounding counties for five members of the national government and five members of the Tharaka-Nithi county government, to exchange successes and ideas to improve the enforcement of the relevant laws and policies;
- organising three outreach visits to Egypt, Ethiopia and Sudan, for a delegation of five members of the national government to exchange successes and ideas to improve the enforcement of the relevant laws and policies;
- organising advocacy activities to exploit opportunities to lobby members of the national government to stop FGM/C.

Furthermore, the fact that FGM/C is a violation of human rights is being reinforced through the following media activities: 
- monthly, interactive, live radio talk shows by local radio stations on the effects of FGM/C, as well as the demystification of myths that help to continue the practice in Tharaka-Nithi county. These radio shows target some 15,000 women, 20,000 men, 50,000 boys and 45,000 girls; 
- using traditional folk media, such as community theatre shows, dancing and singing  performances  to carry out 50 community campaigns using songs, drama, sketches and dance to share health messages related to FGM/C, violence against women and girls and children’s rights; 
- using texting and mobile phone apps to raise awareness and report cases of FGM/C and violence against girls and young women;
- developing and using a mobile phone app that enables parliamentarians to access information on relevant legislation, best practices, reported cases of violence and FGM/C. The app is also available for boys, girls and local organisations involved in the project.

To eliminate FGM/C, the social norms and values that fuel its continuation must be changed. Furthermore, legislation against FGM/C must be improved and enforced.  Men and boys will have to lobby for this and girls must be empowered to stand up for their sexual and reproductive health (SRH) rights, and supported in doing so too. Individuals and local organisations are being trained to act as human rights defenders, meaning the project is tackling FGM/C at individual, community and institutional levels. In the context of this project: 
- people, including girls, boys, and local youth and women’s groups, are being empowered to oppose these violations and are being trained as human rights defenders;
- local development organisations, women’s groups and agents of change are lobbying to change the norms and values that justify and continue this harmful practice; 
- legal and protection systems in the affected counties in Egypt are being strengthened and parliamentarians are being influenced.

All activities in the project are inter-connected. Individual and community initiatives are being supported by a legal framework. Local organisations are playing a watchdog role in the case of violations that have already happened or are about to happen, and taking the necessary actions against these violations.
